        "title": "Objection answered — does grace make Christ a minister of sin? (2:17-18)",
        "range": "2:17-18",
        "excerpt": "But if, while seeking to be justified in Christ, we ourselves have also been found sinners, is Christ then a minister of sin? May it never be!",
        "body": "Paul raises an objection his opponents would press: if Jewish believers abandoned the Law's boundary markers to be justified in Christ, then by Jewish definitional standards they have become 'sinners' (cf. v. 15, 'sinners from among the Gentiles'). Does that not make Christ — who led them to abandon the Law — a 'minister of sin' (*hamartias diakonos*)? The objection assumes that to step outside Law-observance is to enter sin's territory, and therefore Christ has served sin's expansion.\n\nPaul's response is the New Testament's strongest possible negation: *mē genoito* ('May it never be!' — literally 'may it not happen'). The phrase appears 14 times in Paul's letters, always rejecting a false inference from the gospel. The logic of verse 18 explains the rejection: 'For if I rebuild what I have once destroyed, I prove myself to be a transgressor.' The destroyed thing is the Law's claim as the basis of righteousness; to rebuild it (as Peter was doing at Antioch by withdrawing from Gentile tables) is to confess that tearing it down was sin in the first place. Paul reverses the charge: the real transgression is not in moving from Law to Christ; the real transgression is in trying to move back from Christ to Law.\n\nThe argument is subtle but pointed. The Judaizing logic says: 'You set aside the Law's boundary markers; that makes you a sinner.' Paul's logic says: 'I set aside the Law's righteousness-claim because Christ replaced it. To re-establish the Law's claim now would be to confess that abandoning it was sin — which would make Christ the cause of my sin. May it never be.' The objection collapses because Christ's work has not led believers INTO sin; the Law's reinstatement would lead them BACK to it."
